title: For Sale/Trade:  2 Rifles *REDUCED*
postcontent:
I have two rifles previously listed separate on Armslist- haven't had a whole lot of interest in them, so I thought I'd offer them together for trade.

First is an Hakim rifle in 8mm. This is basically a Swedish Ljungman rifle made for egypt. It is magazine fed, semi-auto, uses a direct impingement system similar to AR's, and has an excellent muzzle break to help with recoil. Very accurate with irons.

Second is an FR-8 in .308:
These are Spanish made bolt action carbines constructed from 8mm Mauser actions for .308. They were a stop gap measure before the CETME could be introduced. They are very short, and make excellent brush guns. Has a NATO flash hider and a fake gas tube up front to store a cleaning kit.
I've put 20 rounds through it since I've had it and it seems to be very accurate with open sights for within 100 yards. I haven't tried the adjustable peep sights which range out farther.

I have a little over 100 rounds of 8mm to go with the Hakim and a 3 boxes of ammo to go with the FR-8.

I's like to see these gone; they're taking up too much room in my cabinet, and I have no use for either one. I'm going for a trade value of $700. The Hakim's generally go for about 500 and the FR-8's for about 350 or more.
Would take cash for both or partial or whole trades. Ammo as well.
More pics and info upon request.

title: For Sale:  Diamondback DB9C 6+1
postcontent:
Diamondback DB9C, with compensated barrel. I think the smallest 9mm on the market.  About the size of many compact 380's, but with 9mm power.   This gun has been to the range twice. With maybe 100 rounds downrange.  It's not working out very well for me, with my small arthritic hands, but I watched 2 Range Officers put four magazines down range without a hickup.
I think this gun needs a large hand with a stong firm grip for it to be reliable.
I'm not able to get it to function reliably with my small arthritic hands so I'd like to sell it to someone younger with stronger hands.   It's small size makes it  a perfect pocket pistol, I would recommend a holster to cover the trigger, since it's DAO with no safety.   I have a Galco front pocket holster that fits it perfectly, I'll thow in for another 15 dollars.    You can read all about the DB9 at Diamondbackfirearms.com.  It really is a cool little gun and I wish it worked out for me better.   Don't be fooled by less expensive prices on the Internet, they are without the comensated barrel, (a $119 addition) and you have shipping and FFl charges in addition to the price.

DPMS AR-15 20" A2 target rifle with stainless bull barrel

This rifle is the most accurate AR that I have ever shot. This is a DPMS AR-15 with an A2 stock and a 20 inch long, 1 inch diameter stainless bull barrel. This rifle has a free floating barrel and a free floating DPMS handguard, forward assist, and dust covers. The rifle also has a 6-24x44 scope that has not been sighted in. The stock has a few knicks and dings but nothing major. This came from shooting on a bench. The gun has been fired very little and hasn't been fired since I mounted the scope. 

Glock 22 40 S&W in OD Green

This is a brand new Glock and has never been fired. This is a Gen 3 glock and will come with two factory hi-capacity glock mags. The last OD green gen 3 glock that was new in the box sold for over $500 with $25 shipping plus ffl fees on Gunbroker. This is going to be a collector's item very soon. Especially in unfired condition. 

Sig Sauer Platinum Elite 1911
Price:$1050 cash or $1150 trade value
This is the most beautiful 1911 that you have ever seen. This pistol has never been fired. I purchased it about a year ago and placed it in my safe. This gun has night sites installed. Checkered grip, beavertail grip safety, and many other custom features. This is a beautiful pistol and would make an excellent carry weapon or one to put up as an heirloom. This is the highest end of Sig Sauer 1911's and they are getting harder and harder to find. Comes with 2 sig sauer factory mags.

title: For Sale:  WW-II made Smith & Wesson .38 S&W Lend-Lease “Victory” in .38 Special
location: Between Phenix City and Birmingham, Alabama, United States
postcontent:
This revolver has a 5" barrel (measured from cylinder to muzzle), a parkerized finish, and smooth walnut grips.  Included is a U.S. marked russet brown leather holster ($25.00 value)

Marked on butt: 
- V 2372XX (The last digits of the SN will not be disclosed in this listing.)
- GHD and “Ordinance Bomb” (From approximately April 1942 to about May 1943 the acceptance mark of Ordnance Officer Guy H. Drewry is found on the butt)

Marked on frame top strap:
- traces of UNITED STATES PROPERTY

Marked on left frame:
- “British Broad Arrow” (/|\) in an Oval (denotes British military property) 
- “crossed pennants” with M (?) on left cross; 2 under cross; and B to right of cross (The crossed pennants were the military proof, indicating that unlike many other Lend Lease guns, this gun was actually used by the British Armed Forces)
- “Crown” over BNP  (the BNP for Birmingham Nitro Proof, the normal British post-1955 commercial proof, put on when the gun was sold out of army stores)
- CAL. .38 SPECIAL

Stamped on the frame under the crane:
- M4
- 78699

Stamped on the crane:
- 78699

Cylinder marked with:
- “Crown” over BNP six (6) times (once for each chamber)
- V 2372XX (The last digits of the SN will not be disclosed in this listing.)

Marked on right frame:
- S&W Trade Mark Logo
- MADE IN U.S.A.

Marked on top of barrel:
- SMITH & WESSON  SPRINGFIELD MASS  U.S.A.
- PATENTED FEB 6 06  SEPT 14 09  DEC 19 14.

Marked on left barrel:
- SMITH & WESSON
- “Crown” over BNP 
- .38  .767 (for .38 cal. and .767 is the cartridge length in inches)
 - 3 ½ TONS (this is the proof pressure, - the British didn't use “psi” for their pressure testing)

Marked on right barrel:
- 38 S&W CTG

Marked on under barrel:
- V 2372XX (The last digits of the SN will not be disclosed in this listing.)

Grips marked on inside:
- 505681

The Smith & Wesson Victory Model was born from a war time request by the U.S. Military to supplement their issued sidearms with quickly tooled up civilian handguns. During World War 2, the U.S. Military sent over 570,000 of these pistols to both British and British Commonwealth forces.  The V serial number range did not begin until 24 April 1942. All previous guns, both 38 S&W (or British .38/200) and .38 Spl, were serial numbered in the K frame range up to 999,999 and do NOT have the V prefix serial number and are, therefore, NOT considered Victory models. As production neared one million, S&W considered adding an A prefix, as their SN numbering machine was only capable of stamping six digits.  Someone suggested instead to make the prefix “V” for Victory, and thus this model was named the "Victory Model.”  (Later, the hammer block safety was introduced at V769,000 when the prefix became SV. The end of war Victory model was SV811119, after which the prefix became S and the serial numbers continued, but these were no longer Victory models.)  

… Most Lend-Lease Victory Model revolvers were originally chambered for the .38 S&W (or British .38/200) and many of these were later rechambered to fire the more popular .38 Special ammunition.  A lot of these were refurbished by Parker Hale, Ltd., or Cogswell & Harrison, - but not all of them, - which leads to various grades of quality in the rechamberings.  One issue to be aware of is that rechambering of 38 S&W (or British .38/200) cylinders to .38 Special results in oversized chambers which allow cases to possibly bulge or split. This does not affect accuracy or performance, but it does prevent the brass from being reloaded for use again.  (NOTE: This gun is NOT rated for +P ammo.)  In addition, almost all conversions retained the original .361"-caliber .38 S&W barrel rather than replacement with a .357"-caliber .38 Spl barrel, so there are claims that accuracy for some Victory's can allegedly be subpar when shooting .38 special ammo.  I took THIS revolver to the Range the other day, and shot a group of surplus M41 FMJ Ball ammo at 7 yards, and the group was low at 6 o'clock, but five shots made a single jagged hole that was smaller than a Quarter, and I dropped one shot.  I also shot a group of reloaded SWC, and I stung that into a 3” vertical spread from the bulls eye to 6 o'clock.   I am under the impression that this gun will still shoot it's original .38 S&W ammo without any of the above issues, - but I have not shot any of .38 S&W rounds through this revolver to confirm this idea.  … Based upon it's accuracy, and since this gun is professionally stamped on the frame “CAL. .38 SPECIAL” it is my assumption that the rechambering of this pistol was done by a competent armory.
